<tr>
	<td class="alt1" width="175" align="center" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><b>Gart Egilsson</b>
<span class="smallfont">
	<br />
	Heyokah<br />
		
	
	<br />
	Joined: Jan 2000<br />
	Location: Halas, Maine
</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt1" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p>I didn't try WoW beta, and I wasn't really planning to buy retaili either.<br />
<br />
But I did, and I have been mighty impressed.  The word for Wow is "tight".<br />
<br />
Everything is designed closely together.  The quests gently guide you to new areas.  The quests are perfectly logical, consisting mostly of kill/fetch/deliver type stuff.  They give some purpose to gameplay, and are a great source of experience and money - and the exclusive source for me so far.  <br />
<br />
Completing these quests leads you to new areas, where you end up "binding".  <br />
<br />
I've very much enjoyed it so far.  Whether it has the legs of EQ or not remains to be seen.  It's the nature of the beast that balance issues will arise and players will consume content faster than it can be developed, leading to new content that is not as tightly developed.  <br />
<br />
But it's got a real polish to it, and EQ really lost that.  <br />
<br />
I still like EQ, but with my guild withering and me increasingly regulated to screaming "lfg" in MPG and RSS at odd times of day, EQ lost some charm for me.</p>
	
	
	
