<tr>
	<td class="alt2" width="175" align="center" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><b>pyne</b>
<span class="smallfont">
	<br />
	Lurker<br />
		
	
	<br />
	Joined: Sep 2003<br />
	
</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt2" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p><blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>Sithrax</b><br /><i>It's possible for any class to solo and get meaningful xp/loot, which is important to a lot of people. WoW is much less of a grind than EQ - the death penalty is pretty minimal and xp comes fast in any case. The combination of quest xp, plus the xp you get from killing mobs along the way means you are pretty much always progressing.<br />
<br />
The emphasis on being able to solo is a blessing and curse. In EQ, you were forced to learn good grouping skills early. Zones like CT and Dalnir weren't forgiving of mistakes and tended to force you to learn basic things like aggro management, how not to ruin crowd control, etc. This is not the case in WoW. The abundance to soloable quests into the top levels of the game mean that player grouping skills are often in a sorry state. When you start doing high-level instances with pickup groups, this can lead to some really ugly situations. If you always group with friends, this isn't a problem - otherwise, you have to be careful. I do wish the game would create bigger incentives for grouping, and put them in early so that players get a chance to develop these skills from the beginning.<br />
<br />
</i><hr size="1" /></blockquote>Some interesting observations which I felt the need to comment on. I made some of my characters in EQ to solo and was told by Verant that soloing was a viable option. And by being able to solo I lost skills that made me group desirable. Shamans could both solo and group and were very group desirable. Then they changed the rules, grouping is the recommended/required style and you got penalized or zones/mobs made it difficult/impossible to solo but didnt receive any new grouping skills. Then beastlords came out and pretty much reduced the shamans group desirability and other changes made them buff whores. So much for EQ's version of soloing. WoW is solo friendly.<br />
<br />
And I recall what happened in EQ when you took someone who was a solo class, druid, necro, shaman and bards to different extents, and forced them to group for xp, spells, loot etc., you had the same ugly experiences. Today in EQ those ugly experiences usually happen with Ebays as there are few true n00B's, mostly experienced twinks. Besides the nerfs in the game has made soloing almost impossible in many circumstances. (summoners, unreal dmg output mobs, etc)</p>
	
	
	
	
	
