<tr>
	<td class="alt1" width="175" align="center" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><b>Tugela</b>
<span class="smallfont">
	<br />
	Mystic<br />
		
	
	<br />
	Joined: Apr 2001<br />
	
</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt1" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p>EQ1 was designed originally as a social game where players would be dependent on each other, and that has remained the underlying theme of the game. While some classes could solo, it wasn't by design. WoW (at least the grind to 60 part of it) is clearly designed for soloers, and I think that is a fundamental weakness. The real strength behind EQ was the social structure it build up around grouping, and after a few weeks on WoW it is pretty clear that the game lacks this element. This may change in the high end game (which apparently wasn't in the beta) when raiding/grouping will be required for progression, but the consequence of the game design is two fold (1) most people will be woefully unprepared for group encounters; and (2) large numbers of "casual" players who played the game solo for the exploring/leveling experience will find themselves with little to do and no means to progress other than to reroll a new toon. Personally I think the game population will decline pretty severely within 6 months as the latter are winnowed out, after which it will be a demographic fairly similar to the current EQ. I don't think it will take 5 years to reach EQs age though, it will happen a lot faster than that, players are just too sophisticated in their expectations in this day and age for anything else to happen. I don't think that this is a bad thing, for a game to have a long life it is pretty much an evolutionary requirement. It's probably not going to please a lot of people, but in the mean time they can still have fun <img src="images/smilies/wink.gif" border="0" alt="" title="wink" smilieid="5" /><br />
<br />
As the game ages I expect that the auction houses will rapidly become the primary means of gearing people up, not drops. You can allready see this happening.<br />
<br />
[Edit] Oh, btw, there are at least some locked areas, I ran into one of them while exploring on beta. Probably going to need more than peanuts and a banana to get in there I expect <img src="images/smilies/wink.gif" border="0" alt="" title="wink" smilieid="5" /></p>
	
	
	
