<tr>
	<td class="alt2" width="175" align="center" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><b>Jinheim</b>
<span class="smallfont">
	<br />
	Kilt-Wearing Freak!<br />
		
	
	<br />
	Joined: Apr 2002<br />
	
</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt2" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p>WoW doesn't really "start" at any particular level.  It "starts" the first time you demolish someone in PvP and realize how PvE will never give you that kind of rush again.<br />
<br />
On top of that, the leveling is fun.  It is mostly guided by quests, and all the quests have great rewards.  Whenever you get a quest, it usually involves exploring the land until you find your destination.  Many times, you'll be introduced to a whole new zone, where you'll get quests there to guide you in your exploration.  This yields a much more satisfying experience than EQ's "Ok I'm level 30 now so I guess I can go OT and sit there and kill stuff for another 10 levels, then I can go to dreadlands and repeat until I get to KC."  In EQ, the leveling up was fun for most of us because it was the first time we'd done it.  Every other game I've tried since EQ, I have quickly gotten bored of the level-gaining process and it became a chore that I merely wanted to complete so that I could do the high end stuff (CoH, DAOC).  WoW avoids that, and leveling up is fun again.  For the first time in years, I am no longer in a rush to complete things in a game.  In EQ, I wouldn't waste my time with anything that wasn't the most efficient way to do things.  In WoW, I am more interested in exploration and just having fun than I am with improving my character.  There are level 40's on my server and I'm only level 25.  In EQ, that would have been completely unacceptable to me, but in WoW I just don't care because I am having so much fun.<br />
<br />
Anyways, I guess you could say that WoW and EQ are similar.  But you can say the same thing about every MMORPG that is going to be made in the next few years.  Do you really think EQ is going to be the best for all that time?<br />
<br />
If you tried WoW and didn't like the newbie levels, I'm not sure what to tell you.  Maybe you picked the wrong class, or maybe it just isn't your game.  I had fun at level 1, and started having more fun as the game progressed and my character started developing into a shaman.<br />
<br />
For me, though, the real deal-maker was the first time I went to Ashenvale and happened upon a night elf the same level as me.  When he was lying dead at my feet, I realized that this really was going to be a fun game, and I was hooked.  I try and kill at least 10 night elves a day, now.</p>
	
	
	
	
	
		<div class="smallfont"><a href="report.php?s=7ad5b82dd6bb808099c1cbbff422852e&amp;postid=312681">Report Post</a> | IP: <a href="postings.php?s=7ad5b82dd6bb808099c1cbbff422852e&amp;do=getip&postid=312681">Logged</a></div>
	
